[1] South Carolina
Date: Wed 2 Sep 2020
Source: Walterboro Live [edited]
https://walterborolive.com/stories/colleton-horse-dies-of-eee,32801


Clemson Livestock and Poultry Health (CLPH) officials are warning horse owners that eastern equine encephalomyelitis (EEE) has been found in Colleton and Jasper counties.

Clemson confirmed on 25 Aug 2020 that 2 cases of horses with EEE have been found: a 4-year-old paint mare in Colleton and a 2-year-old paint colt in Jasper County. Both horses had to be euthanized.

EEE is one of the most dangerous mosquito-transmitted diseases in the US. The virus spreads from wild birds to mosquitos, which then pass the virus to humans, horses, and other birds.

The virus is the cause of brain infections (encephalitis) in people, horses, and other mammals.

Symptoms in people include
- high fever
- severe headache
- tiredness
- nausea/vomiting
- neck stiffness
- fever
- chills
- disorientation

Seizures and coma are possible thereafter.

There is no treatment, and infection is fatal in about 1/3 of patients. People over the age of 50 and younger than age 15 are at greatest risk for developing severe disease when infected.

Signs in horses include
- fever
- sleepy appearance
- muscle twitches in neck, flank, and shoulders
- weak, staggering gait
- animals that are down, unable to stand

There is no effective treatment. However, the disease can be prevented in horses with a twice-yearly vaccination.

Tips for human prevention
- Use insect repellent to avoid mosquito bites, especially from dusk to dawn. Look for active ingredients in the repellent such as DEET, picaridin, or oil of lemon eucalyptus.
- Reapply repellent when needed and often.
- Mosquito-proof your home and yard by using window or door screens and eliminating any containers with standing water where the insects lay eggs.
- Protect your horses by having them vaccinated every 6 months. [The immunity wanes fast, within about 4 months. Revaccination at 4 months may be better depending upon your location. - Mod.TG]
- Drain water troughs and empty buckets weekly and remove standing water.
- Stock water tanks with fish that consume mosquito larvae or use mosquito "dunks" (solid doughnuts of _Bacillus thuringiensis israelensis_ which are nontoxic to horses) available at hardware or feed stores.
- Clean gutters and remove leaf debris from yard.

Contact Colleton County Animal Services for mosquito abatement and leave a message. Within 2 days, the abatement team will spray in front of your home.

According to Laura Clark, director of Colleton County Animal Services, trucks can spray in the driveway or in front of a home but cannot go into yards or fields. They will come at night when residents are likely to be in the house and not in the yard. They will not come if there is wind or if a beekeeper lives nearby. (New beekeepers should contact Animal Services to protect their hives.)

